Troy 21-Oct-17 04:45 PM
If you try to create a lot of Random numbers with the same min/max values at once, do they all end up the same?
I'm pretty sure this is just a generic programming question rather than being specifically Dota related, but I couldn't remember if it was an actual problem or not
Because the way random functions usually work is just applying a function to the clock's current state or something like that right? So if you do a bunch at the same time they all will be the same
darklord 21-Oct-17 05:09 PM
I really doubt it Troy, but you could test it by printing to the console.
And nothing happens "at the same time" in programming, things happen one after another, even if its only a nanosecond apart.
If you want to get into the programming side of LUA you will really help yourself to do a basic tutorial of LUA and learn the basics of programming, or else you'll just be playing catchup the whole time.
Jake | Arhowk 21-Oct-17 05:20 PM
noooooo lmao all computing would break if that would happen
random numbers basically work like this-
you take the current time in millis
and you hash it
which is a super long function like 1 returns 084389234983401328, 2 returns 9841231tjoxgju4928r3r, etc.
and whenever you need a number you pop x number of bits off of the hash
when you need a new hash you reference the clock again
if the clock is the same you hash the hash
more info here https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1750
Troy 21-Oct-17 05:43 PM
Ahh I see, thanks
Askelad 21-Oct-17 05:55 PM
random generation works with a seed - that you can choose, sometimes you take the system time, sometime a fixed number if you want to get the "same randomness" each time for debugging purposes
and a generating process - depending on your programming language you may or may not be able to chose it (it's not a hash most of the time)
Jake | Arhowk 21-Oct-17 05:57 PM
I use the term hash generically to refer to all data polymorphization functions, not necessarily cryptographic hashing
Askelad 21-Oct-17 05:58 PM
for non critical stuff (ie not security purposes, or heavy mathematical stuff) like a dota custom game, you probably don't ever need to reset your seed, and probably shouldn't, at best it'll just make it slower, at worst "break the randomness" (edited)
for example if you resetted the seed to the time system each time you call the number generator, you'd risk getting the same numbers if the time is the same, so absolutely don't do that, seed once, then use your generator
